"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893121","Treasury","false","2018-05-02","<p>To tackle the inequalities that children face, in 2018-19 we’re giving schools £5.5 billion to support disadvantaged children. Over half a million of the country’s most disadvantaged 2 year olds have received free early education since the offer was introduced in 2014. And thanks to the government’s strong record on employment, since 2010, 598,000 fewer children are now living in workless households.</p><p> </p><p>The Government sets budgets through the Spending Review process, where we assess all departmental budgets and spending priorities in the round. At annual fiscal events the Government can make adjustments to these plans. In the last budget, this government was more transparent than any other: publishing detailed analysis of the impact of policy decisions on households of different incomes.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-05-02T12:50:51.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893121/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893121/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-27","Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of all departmental budgets to ensure that they (a) include a sum for investment in tackling children's social and economic inequalities and (b) enable policy collaboration between Departments on social and economic inequalities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","139022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893122","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-02","<p>Network regulation, including setting the next energy network price control, RIIO-2, is a matter for Ofgem as the independent energy regulator. By law, Government has no role in this process.</p><p> </p><p>Ofgem states that its proposals for RIIO-2 are expected to save consumers £5 billion over 5 years or around £15-25 per household bill.</p><p> </p><p>Government welcomes regulators and network companies acting in the best interests of consumers and expects consumers to get a fair deal.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-05-02T14:01:02.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893122/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893122/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-27","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to support Ofgem in ensuring that the new RIIO-2 price control framework is tougher on energy network companies.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","138960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893123","Treasury","false","2018-05-02","<p>The timing of the introduction of Air Departure Tax in Scotland is a matter for the Scottish Government. As agreed, the UK Government will maintain the application of Air Passenger Duty in Scotland in the interim.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-05-02T12:51:54.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893123/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/893123/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-27","Air Passenger Duty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what date he is basing his plans for the (a) disapplication of Air Passenger Duty and (b) replacement of that duty with an air departure tax in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","138962"
